<p align="center"><font color="#0E024D" face="Arial"><strong>PLAYER SUBMITTED STRATEGY</strong></font></p>
<div align="center"><center>

  <div align="center"><center><table border="0" width="90%">
    <tr>
      <td>
      <center><font face="Arial"><strong><b><font color="#800000">SHADOW MEN</b></font> - <small>Mercylin, Prexus</small></strong></font><font face="Arial"></center>
<div align="center"><center>
<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="80%">
  <tr>
    <td>
    <small><hr size="1" color="#C0C0C0"><P>
    Throughout Norath there are many camps of shadow men.  Usually they come in groups of 6 with varying types of warriors, clerics and necros. 
Most of the time you might not even notice they are there until you walk right up to them and they beat you up :).  However they can be an  
excellent source of exp for a group around lv 30 because of the incredibly fast spawn times.<P>
The hardest part is naturally breaking the spawn.  It is also very dangerous because shadow men are faster than 
sow and soc.  So make the deal with the group before the first fight, all stay together and die, or die one by one 
trying to run away.  
<p>
The group composition doesn't really matter that much, you basically need a tank and healer and depending on what level you are 
an appropriate amount of damage casters.  My first experience with shadow men was a 6 man group with 2 druids, 1 war, 1 mage, 1 sham, 1 ench 
and it was pretty much overkill, and we were around lv 30.  In anycase the basic strategy is pretty simple. 
<p>
1.  Warrior pulls all 6, you charm one.  People should focus on one mob, especially the casters. 
Casters can be identified by what they are carrying.  Clerics have a little orb, necros carry a book. <p>
<p>
2.  If you are nervous about the amount of shadow men, charm one of them.  It usually best to charm a spell caster. <p>
<p>
3.  The rest of your job entails two spells, color flux and color shift.  Cast them repeatedly one after the other.  
Be sure to time the spells correctly so you can maximize the effect of the stun.  Meaning don't cast your 3 sec stun 
one second after you casted your 7 second stun.  You will occasionally be resisted and become a target.  Have a healer 
watch your back.  But if the mobs remained stunned no one takes that much damage and you still have a ton of mana at the 
end of the fight. <p>
<p>
4.  Keep casting those two spells until they are all dead.  Or one remains, then just dd.With clarity mana regen is improved and you should be able to keep up with the insane spawn rate. 
<p>
Notes <p>
<p>
    Keep the group close together, which is bad for casters when they feel like they are getting hammered. 
    However if they all the mobs are out of the stun radius, or you only stun one or two you will probably  
    lose a group member.
<p> 
    Assist the tank, using /assist, make sure the tank is on a spell caster first.<p>
<p>
    When shadow men respawn try to pull them away from the camp after you break it the first time so you 
    will not have to fight 6 every time.<p>
<p>
    When shadow men necro's spawn pull them before they summon their pets.<p>
<p>
    Loot isn't tremendous.   But shadow men loot should improve with the addition of new quests.  
    when i tried it the warrior only summoned weapons weren't even able to be used by warriors. 
    This is more than made up for in exp. <p>
<p>
    If there are only 2 shadow men, stunning is not necessary.  You might consider using it with 3 
    or more, or depending on how big your group is. <p>
<p>
    Lull and harmony are not a good idea. <p>
<P>  
    Remember stunning also can break a spell caster's concentration, so if you see someone casting
    try interrupting with the quickie stun. <P>
<p>
    You might also consider using mez if your group is well disciplined. <p>

Good Luck <p>
Mercylin - Master Jeweler <p>
http://www.thesilhouettefaction.com <p>



		
    </small></font></p>
